eplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1943.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: You may want to read this (applys to almost everyone)</span><hr size=1>   As for Senator Ted Stevens (R- Alaska) i can speak to his support, being an Alaskan familiar with the man.  I can just about guarantee you he did not receive campaign support from the recording industry- he is an Alaskan Republican that has served 6 terms in congress, SO, the ONLY interest he receives support from is (big) oil, and he really does noy NEED any support other than having his name on the ballot, because God himself could not defeat Stevens in an election in Alaska- he is bar none (even our founding politicians) the most influential, respected, well- known, powerful politician in the state today or at any point in its history. <br>
<br>
  I honestly do not know why he sponsored this bill.  He does have a relatively poor record when it comes to defending our constitutional rights (with, as with most republicans, the exception second ammendment rights), and though I would take offense if someone were to call him corrupt, he does tend to support big bussiniess.  MOST republicans do- as do a good number of deomocrats.  While you are more likely to find a democrat who has the backbone to stand up to big business, that is not to say that they are perfect, altruistic champions of the little guy.<br>
<br>
  Furthermore, this bill (the head topic) does tend to fit a conservative pattern.  It blatantly supports the interests of big business at the expense of the individual and consumer.  It removes constitutional checks upon the excercise of any form of authority.  It amounts to a consolidation of power (one of the key aspects of &quot;conservatism&quot;) through this removal of appropriate checks.  It tends to view the rights of the individual as malleable, and in a sense, more priveledge than right.  Generally, you will find &quot;conservative&quot; legislation to fit these patterns, which is not to say that no &quot;liberal&quot; legislation can.   And whoever said it is correct- more likely than not, there WILL be greater conservative support for this bill, and greater liberal opposition to it (with their respective associations of the Republican and Democratic parties.)<br>
<br>
  But all that is moot- whether you are a conservative, liberal, republican or democrat (or anyting in between or on the fringes) you should be able to recognize this is a &quot;bad&quot; bill.  Unchecked authority is a bad thing.  Authority over us in the hands of the private sector, which is not subject to the strict rules and standards of the government, is a bad thing.  I would imagine there is absolutely no provision for a remedy in the courts for this (ala asset forfeiture laws as the pertain to drug &quot;offense&quot;) meaning the corporations have nearly unlimited power, which if true, would be bad.<br>
<br>
  The things that have happened in this thread- i.e. people focussing more on partisan politics than the actual issue, are the same things that will happen on the floor in congress.  Please do write your senator about this, and other such issues.  I know I have already written the aforementioned Senator Stevens requesting he reconsider his sponsorship of the other bill. <p>  Lonagan Westrider

